      \field{abstract}{Do coordination failures constrain financial technology adoption? Exploiting the Mexican government's rollout of one million debit cards to poor households from 2009–2012, I examine responses on both sides of the market, and find important spillovers and distributional impacts. On the supply side, small retail firms adopted point-of-sale terminals to accept card payments. On the demand side, this led to a 21\% increase in other consumers' card adoption. The supply-side technology adoption response had positive effects on both richer consumers and small retail firms: richer consumers shifted 13\% of their supermarket consumption to small retailers, whose sales and profits increased.}
      \field{journaltitle}{American Economic Review}
      \field{month}{11}
      \field{number}{11}
